article.headline: Shock will face Cleveland in first round
article.linkText: Detroit finishes strong, defeat Mystics in finale
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- For one of the few times in his
career, Bill Laimbeer didn't care about winning.

His Detroit Shock are on such a roll, though, they pulled it out
anyway.

With most of Detroit's usual starters taking the night off,
Ayana Walker had 14 points and 11 rebounds as the Shock (25-9)
finished the best regular season in team history with a 68-60
victory Monday night over the Washington Mystics.

"We were prepared to lose this one, but our ladies played a
fantastic game," the Detroit coach said. "I've always said this
team had tremendous depth, and this game showed that. I just can't
find playing time for all these players on a normal night."

Ruth Riley played just 11 minutes, while Swin Cash, Deanna Nolan
and Elaine Powell never got off the bench. Cheryl Ford (back) was
placed on the injured list before the game, but will be eligible to
return for the first playoff game.

"That was a lot of fun," Nolan said. "We got to sit and
cheer, and they played great. If any of them play well enough to
steal some of my time, they are welcome to it."

Wins by Cleveland and Connecticut Monday mean that the Shock
will play the Rockers in the first round.

"Cleveland is a tough team, and they are going to be a good
matchup," Cash said. "We don't care who we play -- we just want to
get started."

Washington All-Star Chamique Holdsclaw left the game with 4:07
to play after spraining a ligament in her left knee in a collision
with Detroit's Barb Farris. Holdsclaw was carried to the locker
room by teammate Nakia Sanford and did not return.

"We're not sure right now, but we think it is just a ligament
strain," Washington coach Marianne Stanley said. "We don't think
it is as serious as a tear."

Farris and Sheila Lambert added 12 points each for Detroit. Coco
Miller had 15 points for Washington (9-25), while Holdsclaw had 14
points and 10 rebounds.

Washington led by 11 points in the first half, but Detroit went
on a 16-4 run that spanned both halves.

The game stayed close throughout the second half, and the Shock
led 60-57 until Asjha Jones hit a tying 3-pointer with 1:57 to
play.

Astou Ndiaye-Diatta's jumper put the Shock back ahead and
Murriel Page missed a short jumper with a minute to play. Lambert
put the game away with four free throws in the final 45 seconds.

"They didn't play their starters, but they are so deep that it
wasn't like we were going up against bad players," Miller said.
"We gave it our all -- they just beat us."
